full_text:
Linda had recently moved to New York from
Atlanta and had two small children,
but she was brimming with ambition. Those
of us who got to know her at that point
realized she was an unstoppable force.
The best thing we could do was help her
to keep going.
-Lowery Stokes Sims
JAM volunteer, art historian, and curator
We met at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
She was a Rockefeller Fellow at the time.
I remember Linda being suspicious of
me because she viewed me as part of the
establishment. We became much closer
once we started talking and she realized
that I was at the Met to make a living
and to support my work as an artist.
-Randy Williams
artist and educator
Linda left in the middle of the
Rockefeller Fellowship. From what
I understand she was like, "I'm sick
of kissing people's behinds, bye."
-Janet Olivia Henry
JAM volunteer and artist
There were few forums for Black artists.
Linda created dialogue not only among
artists but also with people outside
the art world.
-Horace Brockington
JAM volunteer, art historian, and curator
To our amazement, Linda got an audience
with a real estate company and got a
small space on Fifty-Seventh Street.
I convinced my brother, who was a con-
tractor at the time, to come from San
Francisco and build out the space.
Together we laid down the parquet floor
and put up walls to build this tiny
office with no windows. It was very
hands-on.
-Lowery Stokes Sims
Next thing I knew, I was painting the
walls, scraping floors, tidying up
the place.
-AC Hudgins
JAM volunteer, collector, and patron
Everyone else had an agenda for what
the gallery should be, but Linda wasn't
¡hearing it.
-Horace Brockington
ILinda was always dragging me in to do some-
thing creative. I was like, "Not my job!"
-Lowery Stokes Sims
What I remember from JAM's first opening
sare the crowds and the curiosity factor.
I think people showed up with a sense of
adisbelief that this had actually hap-
ppened. And you could hear a lot of the
anxiety: "Yeah, well, this won't last."
-Randy Williams
We knew how to have fun. We were young,
without much or any fear. We just said,
Okay, how can this get done? How can we
do this?"
-Faythe Weaver
I always say Linda didn't try to
make Black programming equal to the
preexisting alternative art spaces.
She was doing her work, and then
everybody realized they had to catch
up with what JAM artists were doing.
-Horace Brockington
Linda attracted all these different people.
Some stayed, some moved on, but JAM was an
intellectual crucible for different ideas.
Not everyone approved, but everybody came
around at one time or another.
-Lowery Stokes Sims
Linda has a way of pulling you into things.
-Horace Brockington
Linda was never prescriptive. Her exper-
imental vision allowed for a type of
dialogue that you would normally have in
a bar, but it was happening in the gallery.
-Randy Williams
I would say, "These white folks look
scared to come in here, ain't nobody com-
ing in here!" I was the bad guy because
I was saying, "This can't be a hangout.
Linda, you can't have a gallon of wine
sitting on the fricking shelf, because
a few people are going to drink wine and
not go nowhere. We want visitors who come
in and then go home." I was criticized
for having a somewhat corporate mindset,
but I was a business major.
-AC Hudgins
JAM was like those prints that are off
register. Things slid to the left or the
right. The intentions were golden; the
reality was often very hand-to-mouth.
-Pat Cummings
JAM assistant director and children's
book author and illustrator
Linda was supposed to be selling art, but
it turned into a salon and exhibition
space. She knew how to go places and get
the money, though, and she would insult
them at the same time. "Why are you
asking me to come for an interview? You
should just be required to give me the
money anyway."
-Horace Brockington
There were so many times that we knew it
was lights out, and a freaking grant came
through. We were just trying to keep the
lights on.
-AC Hudgins
JAM created this potential for growth
that we had not seen before. It also had
potential for collaboration. JAM is what
allowed for a lot of us to try things out.
-Horace Brockington
The move to Franklin Street gave us an
opportunity to really engage. There were
organizations nearby that, although not
necessarily like JAM, were doing new
and radical things. As a result of that,
I was invited to be a part of a lot of
exhibitions. It created this extended
family. and a lot of these groups started
New people came in. It needed new
blood. It needed people like Blondell
Cummings, it needed Bill T. Jones, it
needed all these fresh people.
-Horace Brockington
Tribeca was empty. When the Food Emporium
opened, it was like, "Oh my God."
-Kathleen Goncharov
JAM curator and artist
At JAM in Tribeca, Linda's taste wasn't
that different. But it was a different
vibe. Being on street level downtown,
there was much more foot traffic than
there had been on Fifty-Seventh Street.
The people who came in were hell-bent
on being hip-their hair was hip, their
clothes were hip.
-Pat Cummings
Anybody could sign up for a studio visit.
There was a book. You got an hour with
the curator. There was a focused, small
gallery downstairs, and big group shows
were upstairs.
-Kathleen Goncharov
It was fairly cavernous, and there was
a downstairs area where Linda wrote all
the grants that she needed to write to
keep the doors open.
-Maren Hassinger
artist
At times we got mad at each other.
Something would happen, we wouldn't
talk for a while, but then-we were
in it together.
-Janet Olivia Henry
Tribeca was a very happening area, and
sometimes celebrities came by. On more
than one occasion, Robert De Niro stuck
his head up against the window to see
what was going on.
-Maren Hassinger
My memory of JAM is all people. I
remember sitting around Linda's desk
with folks, hanging out in different
offices with folks. It was very much
about who was there, not what was
there, in a way.
-Kaylynn Sullivan TwoTrees
artist
Broadway allowed for a different
kind of work because it was a bigger,
slicker space. But I also remember
the challenge of a bigger space, a more
visible space; it felt like there was
an onerous side to it.
-Kaylynn Sullivan TwoTrees
While there were people who were very
much involved in the art world, there
were also people who had various kinds
of political-resistance histories.
There were moments when you felt under
siege, and there were also moments when
that anti-institutional, renegade
spirit didn't necessarily serve you
well.
